      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The opportunity cost can indeed be a bit abstract, but there are ways to estimate it. It's not always a specific number, but rather a comparative value of what you're giving up versus what you're gaining. To calculate it, you can look at the potential financial outcomes of each option. For example, GizmoWorks could estimate how much additional revenue the marketing campaign might generate and compare it to the cost savings or increased production from the new machinery. By comparing these estimates, they can get a clearer picture of the opportunity cost. It's like weighing the benefits of a shiny new set of tools against the potential of a flashy billboard. Both have their own advantages, but choosing one means sacrificing the potential benefits of the other. It's a bit like a game of trade-offs, where you have to decide which option gives you the most value in the long run.",
