    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i get the general idea, but it feels weird to say you're \"losing\" money if you pick the machine, since the machine is actually an asset. isn't there a way the cost becomes \"hidden\" or something? like, is there any kind of risk factor where you don't even realize you're paying an opportunity cost until later?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, the concept of opportunity cost can be a bit tricky, especially when it comes to tangible assets like machinery. When you invest in a machine, it's not just a cost; it's also an investment in your future productivity and efficiency. The opportunity cost isn't always immediately apparent, but it can manifest over time. For example, if GizmoWorks chooses the machine over the marketing campaign, they might not see an immediate increase in sales, but they could experience lower production costs and higher output in the long run. This means that the opportunity cost of not investing in marketing could be hidden in the form of potential lost sales or slower growth. It's like investing in a sturdy, reliable set of tools that will help you build a stronger foundation for your business, even if it doesn't give you an immediate boost in sales. The opportunity cost is like a hidden treasure that you might not realize you have until later, but it can still be valuable in the long run.",
